Docker is a platform that lets you package an application and everything it needs into a light weight, portable units called conatiners.
containers runs on the same way on any machine because they bundle code, libraries and dependencies together.

Docker uses a client–server architecture:
• 	Docker Client → You run commands like docker run
• 	Docker Daemon (dockerd) → Builds, runs, and manages containers
• 	Docker Registry (e.g., Docker Hub) → Stores and distributes images
When you run a container:
1. 	The client sends a request to the daemon
2. 	The daemon pulls the image (if needed)
3. 	It creates and runs the container

Containers are fast because they share the host OS kernel, unlike VMs that need a full OS for each instance.
